<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1437,153,1475]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,267,585,611]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Male.</emphasis>
Similar to the female in morphological structure but with a very similar coloration to the males described for 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="De Geer" baseAuthorityYear="1773" box="[192,306,621,647]" class="Insecta" family="Tetrigidae" genus="Scaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hamata">
<emphasis box="[192,306,621,647]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">S. hamata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[323,404,621,647]" captionStart="FIGURE 23" captionStartId="40.[151,250,1962,1987]" captionTargetBox="[153,1406,196,1884]" captionTargetId="figure@40.[151,1436,196,1884]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="FIGURE 23. Scaria boliviana Bruner, 1920 (male). A. Habitus in lateral view and. B. Frons. C. Head and pronotum in lateral view. D. Habitus in dorsal view. E. Terminalia in ventral view. F. Terminalia in lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3468028" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3468028/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
A–D). Subgenital plate as long as wide, penultimate male sternite with a mid-prolongation (
<figureCitation box="[160,260,657,683]" captionStart="FIGURE 23" captionStartId="40.[151,250,1962,1987]" captionTargetBox="[153,1406,196,1884]" captionTargetId="figure@40.[151,1436,196,1884]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="FIGURE 23. Scaria boliviana Bruner, 1920 (male). A. Habitus in lateral view and. B. Frons. C. Head and pronotum in lateral view. D. Habitus in dorsal view. E. Terminalia in ventral view. F. Terminalia in lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3468028" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3468028/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Fig. 23E</figureCitation>
), cerci cylindrical and with a rounded tip (
<figureCitation box="[736,836,657,683]" captionStart="FIGURE 23" captionStartId="40.[151,250,1962,1987]" captionTargetBox="[153,1406,196,1884]" captionTargetId="figure@40.[151,1436,196,1884]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="FIGURE 23. Scaria boliviana Bruner, 1920 (male). A. Habitus in lateral view and. B. Frons. C. Head and pronotum in lateral view. D. Habitus in dorsal view. E. Terminalia in ventral view. F. Terminalia in lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3468028" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3468028/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Fig. 23F</figureCitation>
). triangular epiproct with a pointy tip.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1437,153,1475]" box="[199,1299,692,719]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,319,692,719]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Variation.</emphasis>
The only variation observed is the difference in coloration between males and females.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1437,153,1475]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
